messageBody:
> I recall from learning to type (proper QWERTY ten-finger typing) we
> used a sentence like "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog."
> to exercise our fingers on all 26 of the orthodox latin alphabet.
> (Count 'em, they're all there!) This sentence is only 35 "letters"
> long, covers the 26 requisite latin letters and is a great short
> exercise to remember for typing.

I was having a little trouble posting at first.

Pangrams are fun.
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pangram

What's interesting about "quick brown fox" is that the phonemes it
leaves out are exactly the ones that TO represents very poorly: sh,
ch, -ng, zh, unvoiced th.

With my western US accent, I'm not bothering with Whitewheat or Ox.

I made some others the other night, but this (53 characters without
abbreviations) is the only one with a fox/dog theme:

"With pleasure, the fox is baiting the dog with more chow: a juicy
dough of fish oil and hair."

Jeremiah
